# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The **1835 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 20 to May 22, 1835, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated incumbent Vice President Martin Van Buren for president and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson served as the convention chairman.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] With the support of President Andrew Jackson, Van Buren won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson narrowly won the two-thirds majority necessary for the vice presidential nomination, overcoming a challenge from William Cabell Rives of Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Van Buren and Johnson went on to win the 1836 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] On February 23, 1835, President Andrew Jackson wrote to James Gwin of Tennessee and claimed a preference for someone who would "most likely to be the choice of the great body of republicans" in regard to his successor.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] He expressed the desire to hold another national convention to nominate candidates for the presidency and vice presidency.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] He instructed Gwin to show the letter to the editor of the *Nashville Republican*.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The newspaper later reprinted the letter.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Stevenson of Virginia served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Six convention vice presidents and four secretaries were appointed.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Tennessee, Illinois, South Carolina, and Alabama sent no delegates to the convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] President Jackson had long planned for Vice President Martin Van Buren to succeed him, and Van Buren was the unanimous choice of the delegates for the presidency.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Jackson and other major Democrats had settled on Richard Mentor Johnson, a Kentucky representative who had fought in the War of 1812, as Van Buren's running mate, but many Virginia Democrats backed William Cabell Rives, the former Ambassador to France.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] A man from Tennessee, Edward Rucker, who was present at the convention but was not sent as a delegate, cast all 15 votes Tennessee was entitled to for Van Buren, and for Johnson for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was nominated for vice president after winning one vote more than the two-thirds majority required.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The delegation of Virginia declared that it had no confidence in Johnson's character and principles, and would not support him.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Letters went out on May 23 from the convention president and vice presidents asking for the acceptance of the nominations by the nominees.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren replied and accepted the nomination on May 29; Johnson, likewise on June 9.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Whigs did not put forward a national ticket nominated by national convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren defeated his many competitors for the presidency in the general election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] While the electors of Virginia supported Van Buren for the presidency, they cast their vice presidential votes for William Smith.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Johnson received a plurality, but not a majority, of the electoral votes for the vice presidency.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1835-democratic-national-convention] In the subsequent contingent election in the Senate, Johnson was elected vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] The **1839 Whig National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held from December 4 to December 8 in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] It was the first national convention ever held by the Whig Party, and was organized to select the party's nominee in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention nominated former Senator William Henry Harrison of Ohio for president and former Senator John Tyler of Virginia for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] With Southern delegates united behind him, Clay led on the first presidential ballot, but failed to win a majority.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won the nomination on the fifth ballot after several delegates switched from supporting Clay or Scott.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention chose Tyler, a Southerner and Clay supporter, to serve as Harrison's running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] The Whig ticket went on to win the 1840 election, defeating incumbent Democratic President Martin Van Buren.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Clay led on the first ballot, but circumstances conspired to deny him the nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] First, the convention came on the heels of a string of Whig electoral losses, and party members were anxious to reverse the trend.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison managed to distance himself from the losses, but Clay, as the party's philosophical leader, could not.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Had the convention been held in the spring of 1840, when the continuing economic downturn caused by the Panic of 1837 led to a string of Whig victories, Clay would have had much greater support.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Second, the convention rules had been drawn up so that whoever won the majority of delegates from a given state would win all the votes from that state.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Third, several Southern states whose Whig party organizations supported Clay abstained from sending delegates to the convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won on the fifth ballot after Clay delegates from Illinois and Scott delegates from Michigan, New York, and Vermont combined to switch their support to Harrison.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Writer and activist John Neal, who chaired the delegation from Maine, claimed to have been instrumental in convincing the powerful New York delegation to back Harrison prior to the final vote.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Because Harrison (born in Virginia) was considered a Northerner (as a resident of Ohio), the Whigs needed to balance the ticket with a Southerner.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] They also sought a Clay supporter to help unite the party.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] After being turned down by several potential candidates, including John J.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden, John Bell, and Willie Person Mangum, the convention finally found its Southerner who had faithfully supported Clay and would accept: former Senator John Tyler.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Tyler was well known to the delegates, having previously been the running mate of Hugh Lawson White and Willie Person Mangum during the four-way Whig campaign of 1836.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] He was easily nominated on the first ballot.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] During the balloting, Clay and Scott played cards with two Whig politicians, John J.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden and George Evans, at the Astor House hotel in New York City.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] When the group received word of Harrison's victory, Clay blamed his loss on Scott and punched him, hitting the shoulder which had been wounded during Scott's participation in the Battle of Lundy's Lane, before being physically removed from the hotel room.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1839-whig-national-convention] Scott then sent Crittenden to Clay with Scott's challenge for a duel, but Crittenden reconciled them by convincing Clay to apologize.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] The **1840 Democratic National Convention** was held in Baltimore, Maryland, from May 5 to May 6.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party re-nominated President Martin Van Buren by acclamation, but failed to select a nominee for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren is the only major party presidential nominee since the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Dragged down by the unpopularity of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was defeated by the Whig Party's ticket in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from 21 of 26 states were in attendance.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] States not in attendance were Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, South Carolina and Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] The 1840 convention was the first at which the party adopted a platform.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates reaffirmed their belief that the Constitution was the primary guide for each state's political affairs.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] To them, this meant that all roles of the federal government not specifically defined fell to each respective state government, including such responsibilities as debt created by local projects.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Decentralized power and states' rights pervaded each and every resolution adopted at the convention, including those on slavery, taxes, and the possibility of a central bank.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was not retained on the ticket, as he was largely seen as a liability in the 1836 election and had focused much of his time as vice president on his own economic affairs.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Former president Andrew Jackson backed James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk for the position of vice president, but Van Buren supported his vice president's renomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Prior to the convention, several prominent Democrats sought the vice presidential nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Among them were Polk; Senator William R.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama; and Secretary of State John Forsyth of Georgia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] The convention ultimately failed to nominate a running mate for Van Buren.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren remains the only major party presidential nominee since the passage of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Johnson would both receive electoral votes for vice president in the general election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The **1844 Democratic National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held in Baltimore, Maryland from May 27 through 30.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated former Governor James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk of Tennessee for president and former Senator George M.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Dallas of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The convention included three former vice presidents who sought the presidential nomination, John C.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun, Van Buren and Richard Mentor Johnson.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Though his opposition to the annexation of Texas cost him support with expansionists and Southerners, former President Martin Van Buren entered the convention with the backing of a majority of the delegates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Before presidential balloting commenced, the convention voted to reinstate a rule requiring the presidential nominee to win two-thirds of the vote.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the first presidential ballot, Van Buren won a majority, but fell short of a two-thirds requirement.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] As the balloting continued, Van Buren continually lost support to Johnson, former Governor Lewis Cass of Michigan, and Senator James Buchanan of Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Though he had entered the convention hoping to be nominated for vice president, Polk had the strong support of former President Andrew Jackson and was acceptable to the different factions of the party.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] He won the nomination on the ninth presidential ballot, thus becoming the first dark horse candidate to win a major party's presidential nomination.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] After Senator Silas Wright of New York declined the vice presidential nomination, the convention selected Dallas as Polk's running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket went on to win the 1844 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] At the outset of the convention, the leading contender was former President Martin Van Buren of New York, who had been defeated in the 1840 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] His principal opponent was Lewis Cass of Michigan, who had served as United States Secretary of War under President Andrew Jackson.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The annexation of Texas was a major issue.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren publicly opposed immediate annexation because it might lead to a sectional crisis over the status of slavery in the West.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] This position cost Van Buren the support of Southern and expansionist Democrats, but he believed that backing annexation would cost him the support of his fellow New Yorkers and other Northeasterners.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren's supporters arrived at the convention with a majority of the delegates pledged to support him on the first ballot.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Cass, meanwhile, had support from a handful of Southern states, but far fewer delegates pledged to him.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] At the previous convention, in 1840, a majority of votes had been sufficient to secure the nomination, but this had been a departure from the party's previous rule requiring a two-thirds majority.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Early in the proceedings, Senator Robert J.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Walker of Mississippi, in cooperation with Senator (and future president) James Buchanan of Pennsylvania called for reinstatement of the 1832 and 1835 convention rule requiring the nominee to win two-thirds of the votes.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Following a historical pattern in which a minority faction of Northern Democrats delivered votes to produce southern wing victories for pro-slavery legislation, the Van Burenite delegates split over the pivotal vote.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Fully one-third of the pro-Van Buren delegates (52 of 154) voted to reinstate the two-thirds rule, along with 90 of 104 anti-Van Buren delegates, producing a final vote of 148 to 116.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The rule would remain in place until the 1936 Democratic National Convention, when it was revoked by supporters of Franklin D.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren supporters persisted in spite of the two-thirds rule setback, garnering 146 votes for their candidate on the first ballot, a 55% simple majority, but short of the now required 177 votes.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Middle and Deep South pro-annexationists opposed Van Buren 75 to 3, depriving northern anti-annexationists the 31 votes needed for victory.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Support for Van Buren dwindled in subsequent ballots from 146 to 99, at which point Van Burenites were reduced to blocking nominations of numerous candidates, among them James Buchanan, Lewis Cass of Michigan, John C.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun, and Levi Woodbury of New Hampshire.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Incumbent President John Tyler, a former Democrat who was elected to the vice presidency on the 1840 Whig Party ticket, also hoped to win the support of delegates, but he was unable to find any backers.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Southern intransigence had succeeded in eliminating Van Buren and his stand on Texas annexation.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] If the Democratic Party was to avoid dissolution at a national level, an acceptable nominee, fully committed to immediate annexation would be required, yet capable of unifying the party in the general election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren was open to deferring to Senator Silas Wright of New York, but Wright was a major supporter of Van Buren for president and had already declined to be considered.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the eighth ballot, the historian George Bancroft, a delegate from Massachusetts, proposed former Speaker of the House of Representatives James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk, who had also served as Governor of Tennessee, had entered the convention in hopes of becoming the vice presidential nominee.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] However, former President Andrew Jackson, who remained popular in the party, believed Polk was just the man to head the Democratic ticket.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Although a slaveholder himself, Polk never enunciated a slavery expansionist position with respect to Texas annexation, as had John C.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Southern Democrats benefited from the Tyler-Calhoun machinations in eliminating Martin Van Buren as a presidential candidate, and clearing the way for the pro-annexation nationalist Polk.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the ninth ballot, Van Buren instructed his delegates to support Polk, beginning a stampede to Polk that ended with him winning the nomination unanimously.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Polk became the first dark horse, or little-known, presidential nominee.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren complied with his party's decision to unite under a pro-annexation candidate, and worked to win New York state for Polk.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Despite Whig efforts to cast Polk as an unknown – "Who is James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk?" they asked rhetorically – he was respected as an effective political operator.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] As a national imperialist, he exhibited an unwavering support for Manifest Destiny, perceived as a non-sectional devotion to expansionism, whether slave-soil Texas or free-soil Oregon Territory.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk argued that Texas and Oregon had always belonged to the United States by right.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] He called for "the immediate reannexation of Texas" and for the "reoccupation" of the disputed Oregon territory.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk's political reputation was expected to diffuse northern Democratic resentment towards the Slavepower, while delivering Texas to the Deep South.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Richard Mentor Johnson had both campaigned for the vice presidency prior to the convention, but with Polk's nomination for president, the party looked to the northern states for a running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Wright refused to reconsider despite Democratic Party attempts to convince him to do so.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the second ballot, John Fairfield attracted significant support, but this was not even close to the 184 votes required for nomination: on the third ballot, the convention settled on George M.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Dallas, a conservative from Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] The basic events of the convention are outlined in the song "James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk" by the rock band They Might Be Giants.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] The **1844 Whig National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held on May 1, 1844, at Universalist Church in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] It nominated the Whig Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1844 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] The convention selected former Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky for president and former Senator Theodore Frelinghuysen of New Jersey for vice president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] While the Whigs had won the 1840 presidential election, the party needed a new ticket as President William Henry Harrison had died in April 1841 while his successor, John Tyler, had been expelled from the party in September 1841 for vetoing bills passed by the Whig-controlled Congress.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] The convention unanimously nominated Clay, a long-time party leader, for president.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Frelinghuysen won the vice presidential nomination on the third ballot, defeating former Governor John Davis of Massachusetts and two other candidates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] The Whig ticket went on to lose the 1844 general election to the Democratic ticket of James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Ambrose Spencer served as chairman of the convention, taking over from Arthur S.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Hopkins, who was temporary chairman in the early stages of planning.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] President John Tyler had been expelled from the party and the delegates searched for a new nominee.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] President Tyler's break with the Whig Party, combined with Daniel Webster's decision to serve in the Tyler administration, positioned Clay as the leading contender for the Whig nomination in the 1844 presidential election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] At the convention, Clay was nominated unanimously.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Clayton, Evans, and McLean withdrew themselves from consideration before the first round of balloting had commenced.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] After three rounds of voting, Theodore Frelinghuysen – "the Christian Statesman" – was selected as Clay's running mate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] An advocate of colonization of emancipated slaves, he was acceptable to southern Whigs as an opponent of the abolitionists.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] His pious reputation balanced Clay's image as a slave-holding, hard-drinking duelist.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Clay, a slaveholder, presided over a party in which its Southern wing was sufficiently committed to the national platform to put partisan loyalties above slavery expansionist proposals that might undermine its north–south alliance.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] The Whig party leadership was acutely aware that any proslavery legislation advanced by its southern wing would alienate its anti-slavery northern wing and cripple the party in the general election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] In order to preserve their party, Whigs would need to stand squarely against acquiring a new slave state.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] As such, Whigs were content to restrict their 1844 campaign platform to less divisive issues such as internal improvements and national finance.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1844-whig-national-convention] Clay himself had previously stated that he was opposed to the annexation of Texas.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The **1848 Democratic National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met from Monday May 22 to Friday May 26 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] It was held to nominate the Democratic Party's candidates for President and Vice president in the 1848 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The convention selected Senator Lewis Cass of Michigan for President and former Representative William O.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] As incumbent Democratic President James K.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Polk declined to seek re-election, the Democratic Party nominated a new presidential candidate for the 1848 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The major competitors for the presidential nomination were Cass, Secretary of State James Buchanan of Pennsylvania, and Supreme Court Justice Levi Woodbury of New Hampshire.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Cass led on the first presidential ballot, and he continued to gain delegates until he clinched the nomination on the fourth ballot.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Butler won the vice presidential nomination on the second ballot, defeating former Governor John A.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Quitman of Mississippi and several other candidates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket was defeated in the 1848 election by the Whig ticket of Zachary Taylor and Millard Fillmore.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson of Virginia was made the president (chair) of the convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] After readopting the two-thirds rule for selecting the nominee, the assembly turned to the thorny problem of competing delegations representing different factions of the New York party.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The convention adopted a compromise (by a vote of 133 to 118) of splitting the thirty-six votes between the pro-Van Buren faction and the Hunkers that opposed them: Van Buren and the Barnburners promptly walked out of the convention, while the Hunkers cast blank ballots throughout.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic National Committee was established at this convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] The main competitors for the nomination were Senator Lewis Cass of Michigan, Secretary of State James Buchanan from Pennsylvania, and Supreme Court Justice Levi Woodbury from New Hampshire.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Former President Martin Van Buren also desired to become the Democratic Party's candidate in the 1848 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Some party leaders asked William Allen to enter the contest as a compromise candidate, but he refused to run for the presidency.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Instead, Allen chose to support Cass over Van Buren due to the two men's mutual support of popular sovereignty.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren, knowing he had no feasible path to winning the nomination without the full support of the New York delegation, promptly led the Barnburners in walking out of the convention.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Bitter and aging, Van Buren did not care despite the fact that his life had been built upon the rock of party solidarity and party regularity.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] He loathed Lewis Cass and the principle of popular sovereignty with equal intensity.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] After it was further ruled the Hunkers would not be allowed to take the vacated seats of their absent Barnburner counterparts, they cast blank ballots during the voting.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] On the first ballot, Cass had a large lead with 125 of the 254 delegate votes cast, with Buchanan and Woodbury receiving 55 and 53 votes respectively.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] On the next two ballots Cass gained a simple majority, while Woodbury's total was steady and Buchanan's began to fall.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] After Cass received 179 votes out of 254 on the fourth ballot, the chair declared that Cass had reached the required 170 votes and was therefore nominated.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Turning to the choice of a vice presidential running mate, the convention picked General William O.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Quitman of Mississippi, former Senator and Minister to France William R.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama, Secretary of the Navy John Y.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Mason of Virginia, and Representative James Iver McKay of North Carolina.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1848-democratic-national-convention] Before it adjourned on May 25, this convention also appointed the first Democratic National Committee.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **2012 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 6, 2012, as part of the 2012 United States presidential election in which all 50 states plus the District of Columbia participated.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado voters chose nine electors to represent them in the Electoral College via a popular vote pitting incumbent Democratic President Barack Obama and his running mate, Vice President Joe Biden, against Republican challenger and former Massachusetts Governor Mitt Romney and his running mate, U.S.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama and Biden carried Colorado with 51.49% of the popular vote to Romney's and Ryan's 46.13%, thus winning the state's nine electoral votes by a 5.36% margin.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama's 2012 victory in the state, on the heels of his 2008 victory, marked the first time that the Democrats had carried Colorado in two consecutive elections since the landslide re-election of Franklin D.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Roosevelt in 1936 and the first time since 1964 that a sitting Democratic president carried Colorado.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This was the first time since 1964 that Democrats carried a majority of the state's congressional districts.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] As of the 2024 presidential election, this is the last election in which Conejos, Huerfano, and Las Animas counties have voted for the Democratic candidate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Incumbent President Barack Obama ran unopposed in the Colorado Democratic caucuses.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **2012 Colorado Republican presidential caucuses** took place on 7 February 2012.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] It was part of the 2012 Republican Party presidential primaries.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The race was widely expected to be won by Mitt Romney even on the day of the caucus, but a strong surge by Rick Santorum across all three races that day carried him to a close victory; however, the delegates were not legally bound to follow voter preferences and most voted for Romney.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Incumbent Barack Obama started off with a wide lead in polls ranging from 1 to 13 points, which continued throughout the early summer of 2012.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On August 6, Romney won his first poll, 50% to 45%.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Throughout the rest of the summer, and September, with the exception of a few points, Obama won almost every poll but narrowly.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Romney gained momentum in October, and the race was essentially tied, with neither candidate taking a significant lead.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The last week before the election, Obama gained momentum and won each of the 4 pre-election polls.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The average of the last 3 pre-election polls showed Obama leading Romney 49.7% to 46.3%.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The final pre-election poll showed Obama leading Romney 52% to 46%, which was accurate compared to the results.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama won four of seven congressional districts including one held by a Republican.
